13. aut illud res publica esset, ‘or that state of things were really a commonwealth.‘ For the syntax cf. i 49 non medicinam illud appellans. For res publica in the sense of ‘ordered commonwealth’ cf. 143 quotus quisque reliquus qui rem publicam uidisset? also xiii 28 manebat quaedam imayo rei publicae. In these passages it does not mean a republican form of govermnent as opposed to a monarohy.

For conscientia belli, ‘through privity to his rebellion‚’ cf. xii 31 conscientia rebellionis. Sacrovir and Florus, two Romanised provinciale in Gaul, engaged in a conspiracy to throw off the Roman yoke.
